I spent my days with Hinata, researching the records left behind by the previous inhabitants.

…For now, I plan on returning Hinata to the elf village during the full moon.

No matter how oppressed he was in the elf village, the elven world was probably better for Hinata than the human world.

Maybe Hinata will live a lot longer than me.

If the barrier opens during a lunar eclipse, we could stay together until my death approached, but that would only be possible if I knew when the lunar eclipse would occur.

It was written that when Hinata's father, the indigenous people, sent him to the elf village, a lunar eclipse happened by chance.

There's no guarantee that such a coincidence will happen to me.

While waiting for the lunar eclipse, which we don't know when it will occur, if I die first, who knows what will happen to Hinata afterwards?

What if after I die I'm found by an elf hunter and sold to a rich man...or maybe I'll be found by someone who hates elves.

Of course rich people are full of perverts.

Maybe someone even buys elves to oppress them.

Just as a slave bought with money would likely not be treated well, an elf bought with money is unlikely to be well-liked.

Moreover, as you can see from the people in the village where I lived, there are many who loathe anything human-like but not human, anything different.

If those people found out about Hinata, they would definitely do something terrible to him.

If that was the case, it would be better to have Hinata return to the elf village before the next full moon, when we knew the barrier would still be open.

Sure, it's a little sad, but it's far better than leaving Hinata behind in the human world, knowing that it would hurt him.

Come to think of it, they said that the path through the barrier was narrowing.

In that case, it would be best to give Hinata back as soon as possible, but he was torn between his feelings of regret for not being able to spend every day with him and not being able to make that decision.

